{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868909/1930111001/0541.xml":{"full_text":"Page Five\nPOWER TROST\nTIVEN SUPPORT\nOF U. S. BOARD\nBY LAURENCE TODD.\nWASHINGTON Recommenda\ntions that the federal government\nsell or lease its Muscle Shoals pow\ner plant are repeated, and hostility\nto public operation of power plants\nand to federal regulation of power\nutilities is emphasizd, in a report\nwhich the special water power re\nsources committee of the United\nStates Chamber of Commerce has\nmade public, just after the voters\nof the country have delivered\nsmashing blows to power trust con\ntrol of the government.\nThis report is one which has been\nheld in reserve for about a year,\naccording to power company gossip.\nBan Secret Memorandum.\nCol. William Kelley, executive of\nthe Niagara Power Co., appeared\nbefore the committee in the sum\nmer of 1929, urging that it seek the\nabolition of the accounting staff of\nthe federal power commission that\nhad been challenging the inflated\nvaluations claimed by power con\ncerns that applied for federal power\nsites.\nThe secret memorandum pub\nlished by The Federated Press on\nJuly 30, 1929, apparently prepared\nfor circulation among power trust\nchiefs, stated that \u201cwe have made\nrepresentations to the water power\ndevelopment committee of the Unit\ned States Chamber of commerce\nthat this accounting work could be\nbetter done by the departments of\nwar, interior and agriculture than\nby the commission\u2019s staff directly.\nIf this committee is successful, in\npresenting this argument to the sec\nretaries who form the commission,\nand further direct enlargement of\nthe accounting staff is prevented, It\nis believed that these departments\nwill not have men specially trained\nfor this work. At least, they will\nbe removed from the direct super\nvision of Mr. King (chief account\nant for the commission).\u201d\nIndorse Power Trust.\nThe chamber\u2019s committee laid low\nuntil the Norris Muscle Shoals bill\nthreatened to pass the house last\nwinter. Then it issued a special re\nport hostile to government opera\ntion of that plant. Now its general\nreport makes good for the power\ntrust all along the line.\nIts recommendations include:\n\u201cThat the federal power commis\nsion should avoid duplication by\nutilizing the field service of other\nagencies of the federal government.\nThat development and distribution\nof electric power is within the prop\ner sphere of private enterprise.\nThat the federal government\nshould leave the construction of\ndams and other structures and the\ngeneration of power to other agen\ncies except where they are an es\nsential part of national or interna\ntional projects that cannot be suc\ncessfully carried out by other agen\ncies. That the federal government\nshould always leave the transmis\nsion and distribution of power to\nother agencies. That the state gov\nernments should leave development\nand distribution of power to utili\nties which they effectively regu\nlate.\u201d\nSERVICES FOR\nHELD TUESDAY\nFuneral services for Christian\nHeld, 74 years old, for 50 years an\nexcavating contractor on the south\nside, who died yesterday, will be\nheld at 2 p. m. tomorrow, at the\nfuneral home of C. Seizer and Sons,\n2016 West Greenfield ave.\nMr. Held died of a head injury\nsuffered when he was thrown from\na wagon to the pavement at the en\nince to State Fair park.\n.Ie is survived by his widow,\n^duis Held, three sons, Henry,\nLouis, and Fred, and three daugh\nters, Mrs. Laura Wichert, Mrs.\nAlice Hollenstein and Dora Held.\nGUY N. COLGATE.\nGuy N. Colgate, 60 years old, died\nlate yesterday at the National Sol\ndiers\u2019 home.\nHe was a quartermaster-sergeant\nin Co. K, second United States Vol\nunteer infantry during the Spanish-\nAmerican war. Colgate is survived\nby an uncle, R. D. Colgate, Or\nbisonia, Pa.\nFuneral services will be held at\n1:30 p. m. Thursday, at the home.\nMRS. BRIDGET M\u2019GEE.\nFuneral services for Mrs. Bridget\nMcGee, wife of James R. McGee, a\nlifelong resident of Milwaukee, who\ndied yesterday at her home, 1176\nFifth st., will he held at 8:30 a. m.\nWednesday at Peacock\u2019s funeral\nhome, 566 Van Buren st., and at 9\na. m. at St. Gall\u2019s Catholic church,\n1006 Third st.\nOne of Mrs. McGee\u2019s sons, who\ndied six years ago. was Larry Mc-\nGee, one of the first automobile\nracing mechanics.\nShe is survived by her husband\nand three sons, William, Thomas\nand James, and a daughter, Mrs.\nJohn Dechamp.\nMRS. HULDA KLANN.\nFuneral services for Mrs. Hulda\nKlann, 80 years old. 1002 Thirty\nsixth st., who died yesterday, will\nbo held at 2 p. m. Wednesday at the\nEdward G. Kaestner funeral home.\n2221 Fond du Lac ave., and at 2:30\np. m. at the Cross Evangelical\nchurch, Sixteenth and Brown sts.\nMrs. Klann married Ferdinand\nKlann in Germany and came to\nAmerica about 50 years ago. Mr.\nKlann. who died 15 years ago. was\nan undertaker.\nShe is survived by three daugh\nters. Mrs. Ida Lembert, Mrs. Hose\nMietritz and Mrs. Alma Janke, and\na son, Hugo Klann.\nThe first, incubator designed for\nrearing children too weak to survive\nunder normal conditions, or those\npremature born, was that of Dr.\nTarnier, constructed in 1880, and\nfirst used at the Paris Maternity\nhospital.\n1 W\nStaff Correspondent\nThe Federated Press\nThree Chicagoans narrowly es\ncaped serious injury yesterday\nCITY JEWS RAP\nBRITISH POLICY\nIN HOLY LAND\nA conference of the Milwaukee\ncommittee of the American Jewish\ncongress, representing various con\ngregations, fraternal organizations,\nsocieties and Zionist organizations\nof Milwaukee, was held yesterday\nat the Plankinton hotel, for the pur\npose of receiving the reports of the\ndelegates who attended the sessions\nof the American Jewish congress,\nOct. 19 to 20.\nThe following resolution protest\ning against the British government\u2019s\nPalestinian policy was unanimously\nadopted at the conference.\nWhereas, at its first session held\nin December, 1918, the American\nJewish congress, with the utmost\nfaith and confidence in the spirit\nof fair play and justice of the Brit\nish people, took the initiative in\nurging that the trusteeship over\nPalestine be conferred upon Great\nBritain in order to secure the es\ntablishment of the Jewish national\nhome to which the British govern\nment, in the Balfour declaration of\nNov. 2, 1917, had pledged itself, and\nWhereas, in a communication of\nthe British government to the gov\nernment of the United States of\nAmerica, dated Dec. 29, 1921, as\nsurances were given that the pur\npose- of the mandate, to-wit: the\nestablishment in Palestine of a na\ntional home for the Jewish people,\nwas the principal concern and in\nterest of the British government in\nserving as mandatory for Palestine,\nand\nWhereas, the congress of the\nUnited States by joint resolution in\n1922 adopted a unanimous resolu\ntion approving of the Balfour dec\nlaration and of the purpose of the\nBritish government in Palestine,\nand\nWhereas, the Jews of America or\nganized a Jewish legion which\nfought under Gen. Allenby and aid\ned in the freeing of Palestine from\nthe yoke of Turkish oppression;\nand continuing in the belief that the\nBritish government was resolved to\nadhere to the policy to which it was\npledged, they thereafter co-operated\nwith the Jews of other countries in\nthe constructive upbuilding of the\nland by contributing men and money\nfor the establishment of economic,\nsocial and cultural institutions in\nPalestine that inured to the benefit\nof the whole population, without\ndiscrimination as to race or creed,\nand\nWhereas, the British government\nduring its occupancy under the man\ndate has failed to create the politi\ncal, economic and administrative\nconditions essential to facilitate the\nestablishment of the Jewish nation\nal home in Palestine, as pointed out\nby the permanent mandates\u2019 com\nmission of the league of nations,\nwhich, in severe criticism, directed\nthe attention of the mandatory gov\nernment to its obligations in con\nnection with the mandate, and\nWhereas, the statement of policy\nissued by the British government\napproved the report of Sir John\nHope Simpson, which is biased and\ncontrary to the terms and spirit of\nthe mandate; therefore\nThe Milwaukee committee of the\nAmerican Jewish congress solemnly\ndeclares that this statement of pol\nicy by the British government con\nstitutes a repudiation of the solemn\npledge given by the British govern\nment to the Jewish people, a viola\ntion and breach of the mandate,\nwhich was satified and sanctioned\nby the league of nations and ap\nproved by the government of the\nUnited States.\nBe it further resolved, that the\nadministrative committee of the\nAmerican Jewish congress be in\nstructed to convene as soon as pos\nsible and take such further action\nin regard 'to this resolution as the\ncommittee deems advisable.\nBe it further resolved, that a copy\nof this resolution be forwarded to\nthe Milwaukee press, to the United\nStates senators of Wisconsin, John\nJ. Blaine and Robert M. La Follette.\nJr.; to congressmen of the Fourth\nand Fifth congressional districts of\nWisconsin, John C. Schafer and W.\nH. Stafford: to the secretary of\nstate, Henry L. Stimson, and to the\nBritish embassy at Washington,\nD. C.\nIt is the opinion of the depart\nment of agriculture that the Amer\nican egret and the snowy heron\nare on the increase. Both are on\nthe protected list throughout the\nyear and are found in a number of\nrefuges and protected rookeries.\nTHREE ESCAPE WHEN AUTOMOBILE BURNS\nHeld to Faith.\nFought for England.\nRepudiation of Pledge.\n1 when their automobile, shown\nabove, caught fire after it crashed\nI against a light post on the Sixth\nFOREIGN LANDS\nBODIES DISPLAY\nCUSTOMS AT T\nTreasures from foreign lands are\nbeing shown at the Y. W. C. A. In\nternational institute, 245 Eleventh\nst.\nThey form the annual Homelands\nexhibit which is a feature of World\nFellowship week observed by asso\nciations all over the world Nov. 10\nto 15.\nWearing apparel and household\ngoods of 25 nations have been bor\nrowed from Milwaukee families for\nthe annual event.\nMrs. Reupen Kaprelian, a native\nArmenian, today demonstrated how\nrugs are woven in Armenia.\nTonight 10 men members of the\nSlovenski Dom, directed by Cyril\nMuskatevec, will sing as a part of\nthe Slovenian program.\nOther nationalities entertaining:\nSwedish, Tuesday afternoon, Mrs.\nAnna Goransson and Miss Edna\nRehnquist hostesses.\nPolish, Tuesday night, Relish Fine\nArts club and the Polish committee\nof the institute, hostesses.\nGreek, Wednesday afternoon.\nHungarian, Wednesday night,\nladies of Hungarian Reformed\nchurch and the Hungarian commit\ntee, hostesses.\nGerman and Swiss, Thursday\nafternoon; Mrs. Harry Bogner and\nMrs. A. Krug, hostesses.\nSlovak, Thursday night.\nDanish, Friday afternoon; Mrs.\nAyoe Herbol and Miss Beatrice\nHilgendorf, hostesses.\nRussian, Friday night; Mexican\nand Italian, Saturday night.\nMORE COUNTIES\nMAY VOTE FOR\nAGE PENSIONS\nMADISON\u2014More counties of the\nstate are expected to appropriate\nfunds for old age pensions at meet\nings of the county boards this\nmonth.\nA measure sponsored by Senator\nThomas M. Duncan, Socialist, in\nthe last legislature made it possible\nfor counties to adopt the plan by a\nmajority vote.\nMaking the pension mandatory\ninstead of optional for all counties\nis now being considered. Eight\ncounties have already adopted it.\nThe amount for old age assistance\nlast year was $67,502 compared to\n$52,438 for 1928. A total .of 392\npersons was helped last year.\n16,400 VIEW\nCONSERVATORY\nMUM DISPLAY\nThe chrysanthemum show in the\nMitchell park conservatory attract\ned 16,400 visitors yesterday, accord\ning to C. W. Davidson, superintend\nent.\nDuring the first week of the show,\n31,500 persons attended, Davidson\nsaid. It was predicted that more\nthan 75,000 persons will see the\nshow before it closes late this\nmonth.\nThe exhibits include 623 varieties\nof chrysanthemums.\nRAILROADS END\nGUT IN RATES\nWASHINGTON\u2014The decision of\nrailroads to discontinue emergency\nreductions in freight rates to, areas\nsuffering from effects of the\ndrought was made over the admin\nistration\u2019s protest and may be dis\ncussed further, it was learned to\nday.\nThe reductions will prevail un\ntil Nov. 30 but the railroad man\nagements announced that \u201csuch a\ndrain on the revenues cannot long\ner be continued.\u201d The revenue loss\nwas placed at several millions of\ndollars.\nThe reductions put into effect late\nin August were for 50 per cent in\neastern and southern territories and\n33 1-3 per cent in the west.\nThe Washington navel orange or\niginated at Bahia, Brazil, in the\nearly part of the 16th century and\nwas introduced into California by\nWilliam Saunders of the depart\nment of agriculture in 1870 through\nMrs. L. C. Tibbet of Riverside,\nCalif.\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER, MONDAY, NOVEMBER 10, 1930\nst. viaduct. The occupants man\naged to crawl out before the fire\nreached them.\nTHREE ESCAPE\nBURNING AUTO\nThree persons escaped being\ntrapped in a burning automobile\nlast night after their car crashed\ninto a barricade at the north end\nof the Sixth st. viaduct.\nThe machine was wrecked. Those\nin the car were Edward Hoffman,\n40 years old, Chicago; his wife, Lil\nlian, 28 years old, and Leona Stan\ntan, 23 years old, also of Chicago.\nHcffman managed to opened the\ndoor and helped the women to es\ncape.\nCouncil of Jewish\nJuniors Dedicate\nMeeting to Peace\nMembers of the Council of Jewish\nJuniors went bn record as sanction\ning the work of the world court at\nthe peace program meeting yester\nday in the community hall of\nTemple F nanu El-B\u2019ne Jeshurun.\nA play, Soldiers of Peace, was\npresented.\nRuth Persion-Lieberman, who re\ncently toured Europe and played on\nthe continent and in Palestine, ren\nered several violin solos.\nU. S. Missionaries\nMurdered in Brazil\nRIDGEWOOD, N. J.\u2014Scant de\ntails of the murder of two Ameri\ncan missionaries and the infant\ndaughter of one of them in an at\ntack on a mission at an isolated\ngovernment telegraph station near\nJuruena, in the Brazilian jungles,\nwere contained in two cablegrams\nreceived over the week-end by Al\nfred H. Vroom. treasurer of the\nInland South American Missionary\nUnion.\nYoung Is New Head\nOf Farmers\u2019 Union\nMENOMONIE, Wis. A. N.\nYoung, Douglas county, became the\nnew president of the Farmers\u2019\nUnion of Wisconsin after delegates\nto the conference here defeated all\nattempts of J. J. Jones to gain con\ntrol. The convention voted to sup\nport passage of a law in Wisconsin\nwhich would place a prohibitive li\ncense fee upon the dealer in oleo\nmargarine.\nMILITARY RITES\nFOR GEN. BLISS\nWASHINGTON Gen. Tasker\nHoward Bliss will be buried in Ar\nlington cemetery Wednesday, the\nday after the 12th anniversary of\ncessation of hostilities In the war\nwith which he was so prominently\nidentified.\nThe soldier died early yesterday\nat Walter Reed hospital. He was\nnearly 77 years old, and had been\nsuffering for six months with an\nintestinal disorder.\nSoldiers from the ranks who at\ntended Gen. Bliss during his last\nillness will escort the body from the\nBliss home to Washington cathe\ndral, the burial place of Woodrow\nWilson, for services at which\nBishop James E. Freeman will of\nficiate. Then the body will be\nborne to Arlington while the guns\nof Fort Myer boom the funeral\nsalute\nRFPAFRQ carried in\nLYAJI mno STOCK FOR\nr toves, Furnaces Boilers\nMILWAUKEE STOVE AND\nFURNACE REPAIR CO\nALSO STOVE DEALERS\u2019 SUPPLY CO.\nNew Address\u20143lo Juneau Ave.\nPhones Marquettes 2907-2908\n^CAREFUL* MOTHERS\n^(Vtoose\nGENUINE t\nHONEYoiwITAR\nEg Ysjagvl COMPOUND\n\"OrTu' nheuknoio/\nWHy/\nB l nasty little colds\nSOLD EVERYWHERE\nThe Labor Movement\nINVESTDRS GAIN,\nWORKERS LOSE\nIN PHONE PLAN\nBy Federated Press.\nCLEVELAND\u2014About 4,000 Cleve\nland telephone workers will con\ntribute heavily to \u201csolving\u201d the un\nemployment problem by being ro\ntated for temporary layoff pe\nriods. The plan has been in effect\nin the traffic department on a modi\nfied scale in recent months and is\nnow extended to the plant, commer\ncial and engineering departments.\nOperation of the plan, which\nwent into effect Nov. 1, is to vary\naccording to the needs of the dif\nferent departments.\nAlthough the Ohio Bell insists\nthat its volume of business reflects\nthe business depression, its stock\nholders do not feel the effects. As\nan evidence of their confidence in\nthe ability of the company to bring\nin the shekels, Ohio Bell stock con\ntinues high on the local market, be\ning quoted between 112 and 114.\nStock in the American Telephone\nand Telegraph Co., of which the\nOhio Bell is a subsidiary, has re\ncently been selling for about 196,\ncarrying a $9 cash dividend, it\nyields the purchaser 4.6 per cent.\nDespite the business depression,\nthis is higher than it was last year.\nFailure Liabilities\nGain 146 Per Cent\nBy Federated Press.\nNEW YORK \u2014Failures in Octo\nber involved liabilities 146 per cent\ngreater than those involved in Oc\ntober, 1929, according to Brad\nstreet\u2019s Journal although the num\nber of failures was only 25.8 per\ncent higher. Bank clearings for Oc\ntober were off 41 per cent from Oc\ntober, 1929.\nEDITOR CALLS\nHOOVER JOB\nPOLICY CHEAP\nBy Federated Press.\nNEW YORK\u2014Hoover\u2019s proposal\nto solve unemployment by \u201cstagger\ning\u201d the jobs\u2014cutting the working\ntime and pay of those now em\nployed\u2014is hit as a \u201ccheap solution\u201d\nby J. B*. S. Hardman, editor of Ad\nvance, organ of the Amalgamated\nClothing Workers.\n\u201cWith characteristic blasts of\npublicity and with no less char\nacteristic flatheadedness and pre\ntense, the federal government seized\nupon the thought of division of\nlabor for the purpose of arousing\nhopes while itself doing nothing real\nor hopeful,\u201d asserts Hardman.\n\u201cAfter a long year of criminal\ninactivity, save loud and tall talk\ning, Washington has for once, al\nmost overnight, come, seen and con\nquered the depression.\n\u201cIgnorance has until now been\nthe basis of all federal policy in\nthe matter of unemployment. In\nfact, unemployment was mostly de\nnied. In its latest preoccupation\nwith the problem, hypocrisy has\nbeen made the \u2018instrument of na\ntional policy.\u2019 Hypocrisy and bluff\nmay carry election day but won't\nprevent disaster and finally\u2014a lay\nof reckoning.\u201d\nf\u00ae I\nMUST BE a reason.\nf\u00b0 r suc popularity\n\nif I tj X>j\nW. 3k /i I if\n-that\u2019s Why!\n1930, Liggett Myers Tobacco Co.\nLabor Meetings\nTODAY\nBarbers No. 50, Miller\u2019s hall,\nEighth and State sts., 8:30 p. m.\nBridge Operators No. 195, Lipp\u2019s\nhall, Third st. and Highland ave.,\n8 p. m.\nCabinet Makers No. 490, 2540\nCenter st., 8 p. m.\nEngineers\u2019 Union No. 950\n(school), Bohemian hall, 650\nTwelfth st., 8 p. m.\nRailway Carmen No. 310, 809\nTeutonia ave., 8 p. m.\nMolders No. 166, 630 Juneau ave.,\n8 p. m.\nriumbers No. 75, 296 West Water\nst., 8 p. m.\nSailors\u2019 Union, 162 Reed st., 8\np. m.\nSheetmetal Workers No. 24, 528\nJuneau ave., 8 p. m.\nSprinkler Fitters and Helpers No.\n183, Jefferson hall, 2649 Fond du\nLac ave., 8 p. m.\nTOMORROW\nAmalgamated Clothing Workers,\nTailors\u2019 Local 151, Lipp\u2019s hall,\nThird st and Highland ave., 8\np. m.\nBuilding Service Employers\u2019 Un\nion No. 17, Lipp\u2019s hall, Third st.\nand Highland ave., 8 p. m.\nCarpenters\u2019 District council, room\n305, Brisbane hall, 528 Juneau ave.,\n8 p. m.\nCigarmakers No. 25, Brisbane\nhall, 528 Juneau ave., 8 p. m.\nMarine Firemen, Oilers, Water\nTenders and Coal Passers\u2019 Union of\nthe Great Lakes, Seamen\u2019s hall, 162\nReed st., 8 p. m.\nMetal Polishers No. 10, Lipp\u2019s\nhall, Third st. and Highland ave.,\n8 p. m.\nModelers, Casters and Model\nMakers\u2019 Union No. 286, Lipp\u2019s hall,\nThird st. and Highland ave., 8 p. m.\nPainters, Railway and Car Equip\nment No. 392, 808 Walnut st, 7:30\np. m.\nRoofers\u2019 Union No. 65, South Side\nTurner hall, 471 National ave., 8\np. m.\nSteam Fitters and Helpers No.\n601, Germania hall, 601 Third st.,\n8 p. m.\nSuspender Workers, Brisbane\nhall, 6 p. m.\nTerrazzo Helpers\u2019 Local No. 51.\nGOTHAM CLOTHING WORKERS\nBUY OWN APARTMENT HOMES\nBy Federated Press.\nNEW YORK\u2014While the British\nLabor party embarks on an ambi\ntious program designed to rid the\nwhole ocuntry of slums, the far\nmore unhealthy and unsightly\nslums of New York city continue\nto breed disease and crime after a\ngeneration of legislation directed\nagainst them.\nHence the significance of the\nblock of modern apartments thrown\nopen for occupancy early in Novem\nber by Amalgamated Dwellings,\nInc., in the heart of the lower east\nside.\nThe Amalgamated Clothing Work\ners were the first to take advantage\nof the state housing act, passed in\n1927, which permitted the forma\ntion of co-operatives and limited\ndividend companies, under certain\nconditions, in the housing field.\nThe Amalgamated Housing cor\nporation, facing a parkway in the\nBronx, New Yory city\u2019s northern\nmost borough, now houses 511\nfamilies, nearly all wage earners,\nmany from the east side, who are\nbuying their apartments over a\nfive-year period.\nAaron Rabinowitz serves as the\nrepresentative of the state housing\nUNION LEADER IS\nTHREATENED BY\nTENNESSEE MOB\nBy Federated Press.\nNEW YORK\u2014When President A.\nPhilip Randolph of the Brotherhood\nof Sleeping Car Porters stepped off\nthe train in Nashville, Tenn., where\nhe had gone to address students at\nFisk university on economic aspects\nof the labor movement, he was\ngreeted by threats of physical vio\nlence.\nA mob gathered on the station\nplatform as the noisy torrent of\nabuse descended on Randolph.\nShortly after Randolph\u2019s arrival\nat the school, the president began\nreceiving protests over the tele\nphone, describing the union chief as\na \u201cNew York radical.\u201d\nRandolph believes the incident\nwas provoked by the Pullman com\npany who feared he was going\nsouth to organize the sleeping car\nporters.\nCol. Luke Lea, editor of The\nNashville Tennesseean, has been\nwhipping up race prejudice in the\nNashville area by demanding that\nNegroes be driven from their jobs,\nin favor of whites.\nthe ministry of tehinterior and close\nPostal Vacancies\nWill Not Be Filled\nBy Federated Press\nBOSTON With a 10 per cent\ndrop in mails in Boston, vacancies\ncaused by deaths or retirement of\npostal employes will not be filled,\nannounces Postmaster Gow. No\nhelp is needed from outsiders for\nthe Christmas season, as there are\n800 regular substitutes to handle\nthe work.\nThere are among the Filipinos 43\nethnographic groups, and the homes\nand customs of these groups differ.\nThe Koran was divulged in 616.\nIt was first published by Abu Bekr\nin 635.\n296 West Water st.\nUpholsterers No. 20, Lipp\u2019s hall,\nThird st. and Highland ave., 8 p. m.\nboard on the board of directors of\nthe Amalgamated Housing corpo\nration. So when Rabinowitz and\nLieut.-Gov. Herbert Lehman de\ncided to loan $350,000 for the re\nbuilding of the east side slum dis\ntrict, a new corporation, Amalga\nmated Dwellings, Inc., was organ\nized to take over the management.\nElectric refrigerators, self-serv\nice elevators, and a roof garden for\nadults and children are among the\nfetaures of the new seven-story de\nvelopment\nProspective tenants make a down\npayment of .$l5O a room, and pay\noff the balance of .$350 a room over\na period of 10 years, after which\nthe apartment belongs to them as\nstockholders of the corporation.\nMonthly rent averages ,$12.18 a\nroom. Total payments each month\namount to .S6O for a 4-room apart\nment of which sl2 is savings in\nvested in the company.\nPrecautions have been taken to\npreserve the co-operative feature of\nthe development. No tenant-owner\ncan sublet without permission,\nwhich is not granted except for\nshort periods. No apartment may\nbe sold to a non-resident, and any\nprofit derived in the resale of prop\nerty goes to the state.\nTAXING WORKER\nFOR RELIEF OF\nOTHERS SCORED\nBy Federated PreM.\nNEW YORK \u2014Plans of the New\nYork bankers\u2019 emergency employ\nment committee to check off \u201cdona\ntions\u201d from the .rages of employed\nworkers for the relief of the unem\nployed is a \u201chypocritical relief\nmeasure which imposes a new type\nof taxation on workers,\u201d asserts\nChairman A. J. Muste of the Confer\nence for Progressive Labor Action.\n\u201cHow will it help the depression,\u201d\nhe asks, \u201cto take money out of the\npockets of one worker and put it\ninto those of another, when every\nchild knows that we have to raise\nthe purchasing power of all work\ners.\u201d\nMuste charges that the bankers\u2019\nplan to raise relief money by taxing\nemployed workers is calculated \u201cto\nshift the burden of raising money\nfor relief to the underpaid and un\nderemployed who still have some\nhold on a job, and at the same time\nto bring down the wage level per\nmanently so that for years to come\nwage earners as a group will suffer\nreduced incomes.\n\u201cThis practice of taxing workers\nto support the victims of capitalism\nand of inefficient management has\nalready been carried to great\nlengths in community chest cam\npaigns. We want to see suffer\ning relieved \u2014but by honest, scienti\nfic and fundamental measures such\nas unemployment insurance. We\nhope workers will vigorously resist\nthis compulsion to pay for relief\nfor which employers and charity\norganizations take credit.\u201d\nRun Staged Upon\nMunroe Paris Bank\nPARIS \u2014The Munroe and Com\npagnie bank suspended payments\ntemporarily today.\nThere was a run on the bank\nSaturday, according to a spokes\nman for the institution, which is\nconnected with the John Munroe\nbank in New York.\nThe bank is a private concern\ndoing business with British and\nAmerican interests and has no con\nnection with the French banks\nwhich wore in difficulties recently.\n6 Million Bank\nMerger for Beloit\nBELOIT\u2014The L. C- Hyde and\nBrittan bank, established 76 years\nago, will be merged with the Beloit\nState bank and its affiliated Insti\ntution, the First Trust Co. of Be\nloit, on Jan. 1. it was announced to\nday. The consolidation will give\nmerged institutions resources of ap\nproximately $6,000,000.\nSidney M. Colgate\nDies in New Jersey\nORANGE. N. J.\u2014Sidney M. Col\ngate, chairman of the board of di\nrectors of the Colgate-Palmolive-\nPeet Co., died today at his home.\nHe was 68 years old.\nChildren's Colds\nCheeked without\n\u201cdosing.\u201d Rub on\nw Vapo\u00dfub\nOVER 1? MILLION JARS USED YEARLY\ni Beautiful Flex-edge\nOWits\nWr Buy at Factory\ns2l $24 $27 S3O $33 s3ft $39 $45\nLifetime Repair Service FREE\nchmitt-Orlow^o,\nEAST WATER ST. BRIDGE\nOpen Till 9\nPage Five","height":"28980","width":"21339"}}
